"burial":{"plot_notes":"Canfield Village Cemetery, Canfield OH"},"parents":{"father_id":"HD2926","mother_id":"X01995"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X01996","children_ids":["HD2928","HD2929","HD2930","HD2931"],"date_year":1826,"date_month":5,"location_city":"Canfield","location_state":"Ohio"}],"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":["congressman","judge","lawyer","ohio_migration","politician","railroad","senator"],"sources":[{"short":"Newton-Oviatt Family History 1875"},{"short":"Funeral Oration on Judge Eben Newton by Dr. Wm Dickson, Nov 1885"}],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["politics","law"],"notable_blurb":"U.S. Rep. Ohio 1851-53; Ohio Senate; judge","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eben_Newton","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"X01997","display_label":"Twenty-year law partner — Whittlesey & Newton, Canfield OH 1821-1841","link_text":"Elisha Whittlesey"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"From Goshen CT farm boy to U.S. Congressman","body":"Eben Newton left Goshen, Connecticut at age 19 with nothing, arrived in Portage County, Ohio in 1814, and worked agricultural land while studying law. Admitted to the bar in 1823, he practiced in Canfield for decades, served as presiding judge of the court of common pleas 1844-1851, and was elected to the U.S. House of Representatives as a Whig in 1851.","number":1},{"header":"Twenty-year law partnership with Elisha Whittlesey","body":"Newton formed a law partnership with Elisha Whittlesey that lasted twenty years — the firm Whittlesey & Newton, Canfield OH, 1821-1841. Whittlesey was one of the founders of the Whig party, served as public prosecutor for the entire Western Reserve, and was later appointed first Comptroller of the U.S. Treasury by Presidents Harrison, Pierce, and Lincoln, becoming known as 'the watch dog of the treasury.' Newton also served as president of the Ashtabula & New Lisbon Railroad 1856-1859.","number":2},{"header":"Brought his mother west in a covered wagon","body":"In 1819, having not heard from his mother Rebecca Minot Newton in five years, Eben returned to Connecticut to find her. He located her in Woodbury, living with a half sister — she failed to recognize him when he arrived. He loaded her household goods into a cheap second-hand wagon and drove her the long journey west to Ohio, where she lived first with brother John in Richfield, then with Eben in Canfield until her death.","number":3}],"open_questions":[{"question":"Was Eben Newton's 20-year law partner Elisha Whittlesey a Hooker descendant through the Whittlesey-Newton line?","status":"closed","notes":"Elisha Whittlesey (b.1783 Southbury CT) studied law under Tapping Reeve at Litchfield CT, then partnered with Eben Newton for 20 years in Canfield OH. Roger Newton Whittlesey (HD0097, gen 5 Hooker descendant) lived in Litchfield County and had children born 1775-1799 in Southbury CT. Elisha's birth year fits the sequence. If Elisha is HD0097's son, Newton's closest professional collaborator for 20 years was also a gen 6 Hooker descendant — neither man knowing of the shared ancestry. Note: Tapping Reeve (X00614, Litchfield law school) is already in the Hooker project through his marriage to Sally Burr. Both Newton and Whittlesey passed through his school.","resolution":"Elisha Whittlesey is NOT a Hooker descendant. He descends from John Whittlesey of Saybrook through a different branch (Whittlesey book #310, son of John #123). He did NOT study under Tapping Reeve — he studied law in his brother Matthew Beale Whittlesey's office in Danbury CT. The firm Whittlesey & Newton, Canfield OH is confirmed 1821-1841. Elisha is documented as orbit_non_descendant (X01997)."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Judge Eben Newton","first_name":"Eben","last_name":"Newton","title":"Judge","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/69/Eben_Newton_with_signature.png"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"eben-newton-1795"},"HD2928":{"id":"HD2928","is_placeholder":false,"gender":"female","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":8,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1832,"city":"Canfield","state":"Ohio"},"death":{"year":1910},"parents":{"father_id":"HD2927","mother_id":"X01996"},"marriages":[],"tags":["ohio_migration"],"sources":[{"short":"FindAGrave"}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Lois Church Newton Mears","first_name":"Lois","last_name":"Mears","maiden_name":"Newton","married_names":["Mears"]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"lois-mears-1832"},"HD2929":{"id":"HD2929","is_placeholder":false,"gender":"female","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":8,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1834,"city":"Canfield","state":"Ohio"},"death":{"year":1889},"parents":{"father_id":"HD2927","mother_id":"X01996"},"marriages":[],"tags":["ohio_migration"],"sources":[{"short":"FindAGrave"}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Thalia Fitch Newton Brown","first_name":"Thalia","last_name":"Brown","maiden_name":"Newton","married_names":["Brown"]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspirati